  <p>Few policy claims are as clean as the one the Philippine Department of Justice made in April 2026. Offshore gaming, Acting Justice Secretary Fredderick Vida said, was fully eradicated — and not just the licensed kind. "There are no official POGOs left. Definitely, there are no illegal POGOs either. That is the policy of the government — no POGO operations in the Philippines." It is the kind of statement that closes a chapter. Two months later, the World Cup arrives carrying the largest surge in betting demand of the year — the precise condition under which any surviving offshore capacity would have the most reason to reactivate. The timing makes a sharp question unavoidable: when an industry this large is declared gone, does "gone" mean absent, or means out of sight?</p>

